\rquote  trade unions, co-ops, Method
ist chapels and Labour Party, religion and labour. Influenced by historians (Halevy, E. P. Thompson), Max Weber and Protestant ethic. Found family, and archive, of John George Harrison, labour hero but disapproved as a conscientious objector. Community, b
ut internal conflicts, e.g. Methodist v. Catholic. Key political role of women in suffrage, pacifism, socialism, which he feels he underplayed.
\par Archival research, interviews and participant observation. Had to send assistant [John Grant] to observe working men\rquote 
s club because so disapproved by Methodists: never went into club himself. Did interview critics of Methodism. Snowball approach; also contacts through two pits still open. Methodists keen to tell their story. Local historical myths: scandal of preache
r and girl, some recounting former newspaper reports as their own personal memory. Noted rather than recorded interviews, except for Mrs Golightly and daughter, recorded for Durham dialect. (Gave this to Beamish Museum; still has interview notes.) Notes o
f meetings, Sunday services and events. Funeral with brass band, communal assertion of solidarity in face of death.
\par Some very old interviewees: one man remembered where everyone sat in chapel in 1913. One key informant a conservative Methodist re-evoking ea
rlier community with a friend. Tom Greenhoulgh, local teacher, still disliked by some because father blacklegged 1926, wanted so}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid11825062 
